observations.recommendation:
Municipal General Services Officer prepare separate property cards on all classes of PPE as prescribed in the MNGAS for LGUs;

Municipal Accountant maintain separate ledger cards of all PPE accounts; and

Municipality’s Inventory Committee conduct the annual physical count for all PPEs, to prepare the RPCPPE and to submit the same to the Audit Team for evaluation not later than January 31 of each year.

Investigate the status of these unliquidated cash advances granted in CY 2015 totalling ₱650,000.00; 

Locate the duly acknowledged received copies of the transmittal of liquidation documents by the ICFAU and to record its liquidation thereafter; and

For unliquidated cash advances granted in CYs 2013 to 2014 totalling ₱800,000.00, make a consistent representation with the ICFAU pertaining to the status of the liquidation documents and the subsequent issuance of its Credit Advice.

Seek approval/ authorization from the Sanggunian pertaining to the expenditures totalling ₱1,772,440.00; 

Stop the practice of implementing generic or lump-sum appropriations on identified development projects unless further approved and authorized by the Sanggunian; and

Ensure that the Municipal Development Council specify the details of the identified priority projects to be charged against the 20 per cent DF which shall include, among others, project location, specific project/program description and specific implementation schedule.

Municipal Mayor issue a memorandum with appropriate timelines in requiring the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, for the prompt updating of Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) and preparation of the duly certified list of real property tax collectibles per taxpayer for submission to the Municipal Accountant so as to resolve this recurring audit observation;

Municipal Accountant to:

Establish its accruals at the beginning of the year based on the certified list of collectibles on real property taxes as furnished by the Municipal Treasurer in compliance with Section 20 of the MNGAS for LGUs, IPSAS No. 1 and P.D. No. 1445; 

Investigate/trace the unreconciled differences, take appropriate actions by providing adjusting entries and monitor these accounts in order to prevent further discrepancies.  A copy of the adjusting entries, if any, shall be furnished to the Audit Team, for evaluation; and

Maintain the subsidiary ledgers of SET and RPT Receivables accounts including its corresponding Deferred SET and RPT accounts.

On the funds received from PHIC, direct the Municipal Health Officer to evaluate the guidelines provided by the Department of Health with respect to the utilization of these funds as well as the release of pooled funds for the benefit of its healthcare personnel;

On Yolanda Rehabilitation and Recovery Program project amounting to ₱3,453,124.50, that Management seek technical assistance from National Government to address the issues on price fluctuation for the biological asset which impede the project implementation.

We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to direct the:
City Treasurer to expedite the general revision of the RPTAR and provide the City Accountant with a copy of the certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;
City Accountant to prepare the journal entries to record the RPT/SET Receivables and  the corresponding Deferred RPT/SET Income based on the certified list submitted by the City Treasurer at the beginning of the year;
City Treasurer to submit the List of RPT Delinquencies as of December 31, 2024, to the Audit Team; and
City Accountant and City Treasurer to reconcile the RPT/SET Receivables accounts with the City Treasurer’s List of RPT delinquencies.

We recommended and the Management agreed:
To seek approval/authorization from the Sanggunian pertaining to the expenditures from the generic appropriation;
To stop the practice of implementing generic or lump-sum appropriations on the identified development projects unless further approved and authorized by the Sanggunian;
Through the Municipal Development Council, to specify the details of the identified priority projects to be charged against the 20% DF which shall include, among others, project location, specific project/program description and specific implementation schedule; and
Through the Municipal Accountant, to ensure the completeness of the documentary requirements prior to payment.

Management, through the City Engineering Office:

Present proof on how the contractors were able to accomplish the work description within the days elapsed provided in the agency-prepared SWA and provide justification on why the reported accomplishments attached to the claims for progress payments were ahead of the project schedules/ timelines indicated in the PERT/CPM;

Submit justification/ explanation on why the City Engineering Office prepared the SWA, as supporting to the progress payments, instead of the contractors;







Submit the Inspection Reports per project stating the results of the project inspection; and


Provide photos showing the before, during and after work accomplished on each project, for the Audit Team’s evaluation.

Municipal Accountant to:

Reconcile the balances of these accounts, and prepare necessary adjusting entries to correct the abnormal balances;

Provide disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements as to the details of the abnormal balances and the history thereof.

We recommended and Management, through the City GSO Head, agreed to:

Verify the actual custodian of the items with PARs that are still under the accountability of officials and employees who are no longer connected with the City, and thereafter, issue/update the PAR to establish proper accountability;

Submit an updated RPCPPE to the Audit Team and copies of the duly approved new PARs issued;

Ensure proper turn-over of property accountabilities of employees before approving the clearance in case of transfer, resignation or retirement from government service so that property records will be timely updated.

We recommended and Management, through the City Engineering Office, agreed to:
a)	Present proof on how the contractors were able to accomplish the work description within the days elapsed provided in the agency-prepared SWA and provide justification on why the reported accomplishments attached to the claims for progress payments were ahead of the project schedules/ timelines indicated in the PERT/CPM;
b)	Submit justification/explanation on why the City Engineering Office prepared the SWA, as supporting to the progress payments, instead of the contractors;
c)	Submit the Inspection Reports per project stating the results of the project inspection; and
d)	Provide photos showing the before, during and after work accomplished of each project, for the Audit Team’s evaluation.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Reconcile the balances of these accounts, and prepare necessary adjusting entries to correct the abnormal balances;
Provide disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements as to the details of the abnormal balances and the history thereof.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor issue a memorandum with appropriate timelines in requiring the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, for the prompt updating of Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) and preparation of the duly certified list of real property tax collectibles per taxpayer for submission to the Municipal Accountant so as to resolve this recurring audit observation;
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Establish its accruals at the beginning of the year based on the certified list of collectibles on real property taxes as furnished by the Municipal Treasurer in compliance with Section 20 of the MNGAS for LGUs, IPSAS No. 1 and P.D. No. 1445;
Investigate/trace the unreconciled differences, take appropriate actions by providing adjusting entries and monitor these accounts in order to prevent further discrepancies.  A copy of the adjusting entries, if any, shall be furnished to the Audit Team, for evaluation; and
Maintain the subsidiary ledgers of SET and RPT Receivables accounts including its corresponding Deferred SET and RPT accounts.

We recommended that Management ensure that:
The BAC submit an explanation on why the subject procurements were not consolidated and procured in accordance with the above-stated provisions;
The BAC Secretariat consolidate its procurement requirements on the provision of meals and snacks of the Municipality’s programs/ projects/ activities pursuant to COA Circular 92-386 and strictly comply with the rules and regulations on procurement under the 2016 IRR of R.A. No. 9184.

We recommended that Management, through the OIC-City General Services Officer and the City Accountant:

Submit justification with supporting documents on the non-observance of the rules and regulations on the disposal of properties to avoid issuance of notice of suspension/ disallowance;






Submit reconciliation of the noted discrepancies between the accounting records and GSO reports and provide them, together with the supporting documents, to the Audit Team for evaluation. Henceforth, we recommended that Management strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 92-386 and IPSAS regarding the disposal of assets, and the derecognition of the same in the books.

We recommended that Management require the Supply Officer to:

Prepare and consolidate weekly the Request and Issuance Slip (RIS) for supplies and materials issued and report the same in the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI);

Submit the SSMI together with the supporting documents to the Accounting Section on time, as basis for recording in the books.

Submit an explanation on the noted deficiency in the allocation of GAD Funds for CY 2022; 

Exercise with caution the formulation of the GAD Plan and Budget with emphasis on the proper computation of the total funds to be mainstreamed.

Appropriate funds towards the capability building of proper officials and employees in the use of the HGDG in compliance with PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended.

We recommended that the City GAD Focal Point:
conduct a gender analysis of its programs and projects through the administration of HGDG tool;
include a training program on the HGDG in the GPB to gain knowledge on the use of and/or administration of the HGDG.

We recommend that Management: 

stop the practice of splitting purchase requisitions or contracts;
advice the BAC to minimize the practice of procuring goods and services by “Shopping” and that bidding should be the primary mode of procurement in compliance with R.A. 9184;
advice the different department heads to prepare and submit a more reliable individual PPMPs to the BAC for consolidation; and 
the BAC through the BAC Secretariat to prepare the Annual Procurement Plan (APP) to guide the City in the procurement of goods and services.
